{{Infobox recurring event | name = Pine County Fair | native_name = | logo = | logo_caption = | image = Pine_County_Fair.jpg | imagesize = 250px | caption = Sunset at the Pine County Fair | date = First Weekend in August | begins = | ends = | frequency = annual | location = [[Pine City, Minnesota]] | years_active = 126 | first = 1892 | last = | participants = | attendance = 40,000 (2017)<ref>https://conservancy.umn.edu/bitstream/handle/11299/198775/Pine%20County%20Fair%20report%20combined%20FINAL--editBS2018.04.04.pdf?sequence=1</ref> | genre = County fair | budget = | patron = | website = [http://www.pinecountyfair.com/ pinecountyfair.com] | footnotes = }} The '''Pine County Fair''' is an annual event held at the [[Pine County, Minnesota|Pine County]] Fairgrounds in [[Pine City, Minnesota]], United States. The [[fair]], like many in Minnesota, includes [[amusement ride]]s, live entertainment and exhibits of [[Livestock|farm animals]], [[food]], and [[Floral design|flowers]] along with other types of specialty displays. Youth members of [[4-H]] and [[Future Farmers of America]] participate by showing their animals and specialty collections. ===Demolition derby=== Pine County Fair’s biggest draw is the Demolition Derby. Considered the “hardest hitting demolition derby in the Midwest”,<ref>https://www.tpt.org/derby-fever-the-movie/</ref> the derby draws around 100 registrants each year and sells thousands of tickets, bringing in one-third of the total spending at the fair each year.<ref>http://www.pinecitymn.com/news/study-pine-county-fair-brings-in-k/article_227f750c-5557-11e8-ad27-6f85894ae696.html</ref> It is held during the first weekend of August. [[File:DemoDerby.jpg|thumb|Cars lined up prior to the Pine County Fair demolition derby.]] ==History== * From 1872-1888 Pine County and [[Chisago County, Minnesota|Chisago County]] held a joint fair.<ref>https://www.pinecityhistory.com/uploads/2/1/5/2/21527228/pinecountyfairsmall_reduced.pdf</ref> * In 1911, Governor [[Adolph Olson Eberhart]] spoke at the fair. * In 1939, [[Cedric Adams]] and [[Clellan Card]] were Master of Ceremonies at the grandstand. * In 1978, the first [[International Polkafest]] was held at the Pine County Fairgrounds and it was held there until it outgrew the space.<ref>https://www.virginiamn.com/news/local/famed-polkafest-enters-th-year/article_b06131dc-3c64-11e8-bfd0-2f8c45f21787.html</ref> * In 1996, the grandstand was burned in a fire and later rebuilt with the help of the Pine City [[Lions Clubs International|Lions]].<ref>http://www.pinecitymn.com/news/pine-city-lions-celebrate-half-century-of-service/article_fe47846c-6643-11e6-81e5-b39487227b57.html</ref> * In 2014, the movie ''Derby Fever'', by Dell Gross, about the Pine County Fair demotion derby, was released and shown at the [[Highway 61 Film Festival]].<ref>https://www.presspubs.com/pine_city/news/article_3cf6423c-141d-11e4-a8fc-0019bb2963f4.html</ref> * In 2018, a new [[beer garden]] and event center debuted at the Pine County Fairgrounds.<ref>http://www.pinecitymn.com/news/new-beer-garden-makes-debut-at-th-pine-county-fair/article_2f7450e4-76fe-11e7-b4cc-9f2616a0b842.html</ref>
