[[File:London Six Day 1967 Polaroid (23808947444).jpg|thumb|The 1967 edition held at the [[Earls Court Exhibition Centre]]]]
The '''Six Days of London''' is a [[Six-day racing|six-day track cycling race]] held annually in [[London]], United Kingdom. 

==History==
A first edition of the event was held in 1903, when 4 couples of riders competed 6 hours per day from 2 to 7 February at [[Alexandra Palace]]. The winning couple, England's [[Tommy Hall (cyclist)|Hall]] and Martin, rode a total amount of 839 miles.<ref>http://www.sixday.org.uk/html/1903_london.html</ref> After that edition the Six Days race was not to return until 1923.<ref>http://memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/piste_6jours/6j_londres.php</ref> The event wasn't held since 1980, but was revived in 2015. 

Between 1936 and 1980 the event was held at the [[Wembley Arena]] on a {{convert|166|m|abbr=on}} temporary track. Since 2015, the event is held at the velodrome of the [[Lee Valley VeloPark]].

